The nonwhite districts, which included many large cities, were much larger than the white districts, which included many small rural areas.
But the overall gap in state and local funding was $23 billion.
ADOverall, the report found 21 states where white districts got more funding and 14 states where nonwhite districts got more.
The gap was most dramatic in Arizona, where white districts were given $7,613 more per student than nonwhite districts.
He said conservatives should realize that if school funding were more even, it would bolster school choice programs, which many conservatives back.